# 🔑 Core Concepts Explained (with Code)

## 1. WebSockets vs HTTP
**Explanation:** HTTP is a one-way street where the client asks for data and the server responds, then closes the connection. WebSockets are a persistent, two-way open pipeline. The server can "push" data to the client at any time without the client asking. This is essential for real-time apps.
**Why it is used:** If we used HTTP, the client would have to constantly refresh (poll) the server every second to ask "did anyone type anything?". WebSockets allow the server to instantly tell the client "User B typed 'X'".

## 2. Socket.IO rooms
**Explanation:** A way to group connections.
**Code:**
```javascript
// In App.jsx
const provider = new SocketIOProvider("/", "monaco", ydoc, {
  autoConnect: true,
})
```
**Breakdown:** The string `"monaco"` is the room (or document name). `y-socket.io` tells Socket.IO to put this user in the "monaco" room.
**Why it is used:** To support multiple separate documents. If you later create a URL like `?room=test`, you can pass `test` instead of `"monaco"`, isolating those users.

## 3. Yjs (CRDT concept, simplified)
**Explanation:** CRDT stands for Conflict-free Replicated Data Type. Think of it as a smart data structure. Instead of saving "The text is now 'Hello'", it saves "User A inserted 'H' at pos 0, 'e' at pos 1...". It ensures that no matter in what order updates arrive via the internet, everyone ends up with the exact same text.
**Why it is used:** To avoid "locking" the document (where only one person can type at a time) and to magically resolve conflicts when two people type at exactly the same moment.

## 4. Document synchronization
**Explanation:** Creating the shared data structures that Yjs will track.
**Code:**
```javascript
// In App.jsx
const ydoc = useMemo(() => new Y.Doc(), [])
const yText = useMemo(() => ydoc.getText("monaco"), [ ydoc ])
```
**Breakdown:** `new Y.Doc()` creates the local brain for Yjs. `.getText("monaco")` creates a specific shared text type inside that document. We use `useMemo` so React doesn't recreate the document on every re-render.
**Why it is used:** This is the actual data layer that holds your collaborative code.

## 5. Awareness (user presence)
**Explanation:** Sharing temporary state like "who is online" or "where is their cursor?". This data isn't saved to the document permanently; it's ephemeral.
**Code:**
```javascript
// In App.jsx
provider.awareness.setLocalStateField("user", { username })

provider.awareness.on("change", () => {
  const states = Array.from(provider.awareness.getStates().values())
  setUsers(states.filter(state => state.user).map(state => state.user))
})
```
**Breakdown:** We set our local awareness state with our `username`. We listen to the `change` event. When anyone joins or leaves, the awareness network updates, and we grab all states to update our React `users` list sidebar.
**Why it is used:** For building the "Active Users" sidebar and, later, remote cursors.

## 6. Editor binding (Yjs + editor)
**Explanation:** Connecting the smart Yjs text structure to the dumb visual UI editor.
**Code:**
```javascript
// In App.jsx
const handleMount = (editor) => {
  editorRef.current = editor
  new MonacoBinding(yText, editorRef.current.getModel(), new Set([ editorRef.current ]))
}
```
**Breakdown:** `MonacoBinding` is the glue. It listens to changes in `editorRef.current.getModel()` (Monaco) and writes them to `yText` (Yjs). It also listens to `yText` and writes them back to Monaco.
**Why it is used:** So you don't have to manually write `onChange` handlers to sync Monaco with Yjs.

